column42: There was a lack of clear expectations on some assignments, and some modules had instructions that contradicted what was in the assignment pages. The work is stressful enough without having to figure out what needed to be submitted.
column43: The organization of modules into biology, coding, etc., allowed me to know what to expect and prepare myself for each section.
column88:
Previously, cataloging the root microbiome of rice crops. 
This time, analyzing gene expression to predict the sex chromosome complement of cell lines in the CCLE database.

column42: The thought of not being able to trust myself in generating meaningful findings increased my feelings of anxiousness at first, but this feeling slightly dropped bellow average after I have gone through the course and got my work done.
column43: Realizing that the instructors' expectations of the study from us was not to provide definitive novel work, but rather to go through the investigation as a team and sharing what we find. This shared atmosphere of exploration and sharing of findings has significantly decreased my feelings of anxiousness.
column88: I collaborated with a teammate to conduct research on "Boundary Strength Assessment of Free Vibrating Beams: A Computational Approach." We compiled reports, scripts, and simulations for a client from South Korea and presented our findings at a conference seminar held at the University of Massachusetts Amherst.

column42:
The tight timelines of turning around assignments. I did not have an easy class load, and having this only as a B session class is crazy, I defiantly recommend it to be changed to C session.
Also, I was quite frustrated why the required class for this research experience only taught command, and then this experience required advance knowledge of R.
column43: Flexibility with grading efforts. Dr. Plaisier, was defiantly reassuring to say it is based on effort and not being perfect. She helped explain alternative ways to perform the tasks to ensure I was able to participate.
column82: Executive Director at Clinical Research Organization

column42: Attempting to write my own novel code to come up with figures/graphs made me anxious at first. I did become more comfortable with this over time. Knowing what questions to ask that were relevant to the research gave me the most anxiety throughout this course.
column43: Starting with a drafted R code really reduced my feelings of anxiety about writing my own code.

column42: The unfamiliarity with R programming while trying to overcome issues in the short time we had between modules.

column42:
This is no fault of the instructional team, however, the lack of lab meetings on weekends and outside of normal work hours made me feel a bit left out, and therefore a bit lost and anxious. 
I also felt rushed at the end with our manuscripts. I understand that this is a 7 week course, and that the R Tutorials at the beginning were necessary for those who have no R experience, however, I felt that another week on the manuscripts would have been helpful.
column43: The slack channel and the discord helped quite a lot. And the way that the weekly progress reports were graded based on efforts, and allowed students to communicate how they were doing took a lot of the stress away. It helped just to see that everyone was struggling a bit, and that just comes with the territory of learning a new skill.

column43: When we began coding in R, it became more accessible to me. I know I am not the smartest person in the world, but when I attended lab meetings, read Slack messages, and found that many of my classmates had the same feelings of confusion as I did, it made me feel better about my report.

column42: The amount of material we had to learn within a 7-week period felt overwhelming at times. I also struggled quite a bit with R, though I feel I eventually learned and improved. I have never written a scientific paper previously, so writing one here for the first time felt daunting.

column81: Professional degree (e.g. MD, DDS, DVM, JD)

column42: The only aspect of this CURE that increased my feelings of anxiousness was the coding part. It was a little stressful and sometimes confusing navigating the software carpentry program. But the main reason why I felt anxious was because I fell behind due to some personal circumstances and I had a hard time catching up. It made me anxious to not be able to preform as well as I know I could and to not be in sync with my peers. I feel like the coding part would not have been as stressful if it had videos that show how to do some of the tasks, especially when it came to building our code and final manuscript.
column43: What decreased my feelings of stress was how interactive, vocal, and involved Dr. Wilson and Dr. Plaisier were. It was so easy to ask questions and they were both so nice, helpful, and nurturing. It really made everything so much better. Another thing that decreased my feelings of stress was how interactive the class was. A lot of question asking, helping each other, office hours and writing hours, it was very nice and I really enjoyed this research experience and I'm very grateful that I got to be a part of it.
